This first lesson is about trigonometry

3
00:00:03,933 --> 00:00:08,433
We're going to talk about 3 topics: 
the first one concerns trigonometric functions

4
00:00:08,433 --> 00:00:12,966
We'll talk about addition formula, 
which are the most important formula

5
00:00:12,966 --> 00:00:17,599
at last, 
we'll show how to solve a trigonometric equation

6
00:00:17,600 --> 00:00:22,700
Concerning trigonometric functions,

7
00:00:22,700 --> 00:00:27,400
we have represented here 
what we call the trigonometric circle. 
This circle

8
00:00:27,400 --> 00:00:32,100
is the circle with center O, the origin, 
and with 1 as radius.

9
00:00:32,100 --> 00:00:36,266
On the circle, 
we've put an angle, alpha,

10
00:00:36,266 --> 00:00:41,432
in violet, 
and this angle determines a point on the circle.

11
00:00:41,433 --> 00:00:46,233
This point admits coordinates. 
Its coordinates

12
00:00:46,233 --> 00:00:49,099
are depending on the angle alpha.

13
00:00:49,100 --> 00:00:57,400
And its coordinates are precisely the so-called trigonometric functions, namely on the x-axis, the length over there

14
00:00:57,400 --> 00:01:00,633
we define what we call the cosine of alpha

15
00:01:00,633 --> 00:01:06,733
and on the y-axis, 
we define what we call the sinus of alpha.

16
00:01:06,733 --> 00:01:09,233
We can define ...

17
00:01:09,233 --> 00:01:15,766
a third trigonometric function: drawing the half-line over there,

18
00:01:15,766 --> 00:01:23,032
and drawing the vertical line passing through the point (1,0).

19
00:01:23,033 --> 00:01:26,533
If we take the intersection of these two straight lines

20
00:01:26,533 --> 00:01:30,933
then the height in green over there

21
00:01:30,933 --> 00:01:34,799
also depends on alpha. 
Because if I move alpha

22
00:01:34,800 --> 00:01:36,666
then the height is moving too,

23
00:01:36,666 --> 00:01:41,666
and this height is called the tangent of alpha.

24
00:01:41,666 --> 00:01:50,799
So we can see a very important property, 
which relies the three trigonometric functions :

25
00:01:50,800 --> 00:01:55,333
thanks to Thales' theorem. 
Indeed here you have a triangle

26
00:01:55,333 --> 00:01:59,633
and inside of it, you can find
this segment over there

27
00:01:59,633 --> 00:02:02,433
and this one, which are parallel.

28
00:02:02,433 --> 00:02:06,366
Thales' theorem says that the quotient between

29
00:02:06,366 --> 00:02:14,332
the length of this segment and the lenght of this one is equal to the quotient between the length of the segment over there

30
00:02:14,333 --> 00:02:16,499
and the one over there.

31
00:02:16,500 --> 00:02:20,700
Namely,
sinus of alpha

32
00:02:20,700 --> 00:02:27,400
divided by tangent of alpha is equal to cosine of alpha divided by the length of the large segment which is 1.

33
00:02:27,400 --> 00:02:30,366
This can be rewritten,

34
00:02:30,366 --> 00:02:37,166
this is the well-known formula, as tangent of alpha equals sinus of alpha over cosine of alpha.

35
00:02:37,166 --> 00:02:41,666
This is a first and very useful property. A second property

36
00:02:41,666 --> 00:02:45,266
comes from
the little triangle over here.

37
00:02:45,266 --> 00:02:48,199
This little triangle has a 90 degrees-angle.

38
00:02:48,200 --> 00:02:51,333
In this kind of triangle, 
we can apply the Pythagoras' Theorem.

39
00:02:51,333 --> 00:02:55,366
It says that
the sum of the length squared 

40
00:02:55,366 --> 00:03:03,099
here and here is equal to the length squared of the larger segment. Its length equals 1

41
00:03:03,100 --> 00:03:08,333
whatever the value
of alpha.

42
00:03:08,333 --> 00:03:13,433
So Pythagoras' Theorem says: the length over here, sinus of x ...

43
00:03:13,433 --> 00:03:21,966
... squared plus the length over here, 
cosine of x squared, is equal to 1 squared.

44
00:03:21,966 --> 00:03:26,966
Finally, we can recall usual values.

45
00:03:26,966 --> 00:03:31,966
We put the usual values: 
Pi/6, Pi/4, Pi/3.

46
