47
00:03:33,066 --> 00:03:34,999
You absolutely need to know

48
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:38,033
the cosine values of these usual values

49
00:03:38,033 --> 00:03:43,899
and the sinus values too.

50
00:03:43,900 --> 00:03:51,933
Once we know the usual values, 
how to compute other values such that sinus of -Pi/3 ?

51
00:03:51,933 --> 00:03:56,533
We're going to see some symmetry properties.

52
00:03:56,533 --> 00:04:01,866
We have the trigonometric circle with an angle, called x.

53
00:04:01,866 --> 00:04:08,666
Now we're looking the angle -x. 
It's going to the other side.

54
00:04:08,666 --> 00:04:12,432
We're looking for its coordinates.

55
00:04:12,433 --> 00:04:20,633
Its coordinates: 
on the x-axis, one can see that the cosine of -x, 
the length over here, is exactly the same as

56
00:04:20,633 --> 00:04:26,099
the cosine of x. 
So we get a first property: 
cosine of -x equals cosine of x.

57
00:04:26,100 --> 00:04:30,966
By contrast, the sinus of -x, 
the y-coordinate here, 

58
00:04:30,966 --> 00:04:37,499
is the same length as the sinus of x, 
but with a negative sign in front of. 

59
00:04:37,500 --> 00:04:44,066
So sinus of -x equals - sinus of x. 
This can be used to determine

60
00:04:44,066 --> 00:04:51,066
this kind of value. 
For example, what is the value of sinus of -Pi/3 ?

61
00:04:51,066 --> 00:04:58,099
sinus of -Pi/3 is actually - sinus of Pi/3, 
namely - the square root of 3 over 2.

62
00:04:58,100 --> 00:05:02,700
Now, 
how to compute the cosine of 2Pi/3 ?

63
00:05:02,700 --> 00:05:04,966
Again we need

64
00:05:04,966 --> 00:05:10,799
some other symmetry properties. 
For example, with x given, we can draw

65
00:05:10,800 --> 00:05:16,100
the angle x + Pi/2: 
I take x and turn of one quarter.

66
00:05:16,100 --> 00:05:19,033
We get the green angle over there.

67
00:05:19,033 --> 00:05:23,466
We're looking for the coordinates of this angle.

68
00:05:23,466 --> 00:05:27,832
The height over here,
I can draw it,

69
00:05:27,833 --> 00:05:34,766
I can see that the sinus of x+Pi/2 has actually the same value as

70
00:05:34,766 --> 00:05:42,532
the cosine of x. 
We get a first relation: 
sinus of x+Pi/2 equals cosine of x.

71
00:05:42,533 --> 00:05:49,166
This time, I'm interested in 
its x-coordinate.

72
00:05:49,166 --> 00:05:52,632
I can see that the cosine of x+Pi/2

73
00:05:52,633 --> 00:05:59,633
has exactly the same length as the sinus of x, but with a negative sign in front of it (because we are on the negative side over the x-axis).

74
00:05:59,633 --> 00:06:06,766
We get the formula: cosine of x+Pi/2 
equals - sinus of x.

75
00:06:06,766 --> 00:06:13,299
It is useful to compute this value. 
Indeed 2Pi/3 ...

76
00:06:13,300 --> 00:06:20,866
can be rewritten as the sum of two angles: Pi/6 + Pi/2. 
And we know that the cosine of x

77
00:06:20,866 --> 00:06:31,066
+Pi/2 is equal to - sinus of x, namely -sinus of Pi/6, 
and we finally get a well-known usual value.

78
00:06:31,066 --> 00:06:35,399
We know that sinus of Pi/6 is equal to one half.

